<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06216188 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06216188 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Plaskett  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  AVIATION; COMPANY; EMPLOYEE; END  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Pan Am Corp. on Friday announced heavy layoffs and quarterly operating lossesbecause of the sickly airline's precarious financial condition.;    It willfurlough 5,000 employees, nearly a quarter of the workforce, in a seasonalshrinkage that is worse than usual this year.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  PAN AM ANNOUNCES 5,000 LAYOFFS, LOSSCARRIER CUTTING QUARTER OF WORKFORCE  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The struggling airline, in bankruptcy court since January, also announcedit earned $99.9 million in the April-June quarter, but only because it soldUnited Airlines routes into London's Heathrow Airport that were once the heartof Pan Am's trans-Atlantic operations.;    United Airlines bought the Londonroutes for $260 million. The infusion masked Pan Am's operating loss of $125.3million for the quarter.;    Pan Am once was the nation's premierinternational airline, and its travails have come to symbolize the financialplight of the U.S. airline industry, hurt by the recession and falloff inriders. Pan Am has been trying to sell pieces of itself to satisfy creditorclaims.;    Also on Friday, Pan Am Chairman Thomas G. Plaskett wroteTransportation Secretary Samuel K. Skinner to say Pan Am has been consideringin good faith all offers for its assets.;    Pan Am spokesman JeffreyKriendler said, &quot;The purpose of his response was to set the secretary onnotice that we have done what he asked us to do.&quot;;    It was unclear whatmotivated Skinner to write Pan Am.;    Pan Am included the announcement of thelayoffs at the bottom of an earnings statement.;    The airline said it &quot;wouldbe issuing furlough notices to approximately 5,000 employees in all workcategories over the next few weeks, reflecting significantly deeper schedulereductions from the summer peak than in prior years.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  New York  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910803  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  August  </MONTH><PG.COL>  11F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  273  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday August 3, 199100216188,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>